Abortion in Djibouti is only legal under a narrow range of conditions. Under Article 368 of the Criminal Code, the termination of pregnancy is allowed only to protect the life, health or the mental health of the woman involved, when the foetus is deformed or at risk of developing a serious illness, or for proven cases of rape. The word ‘health’ has been interpreted to include psychological health. These grounds may only be used on written recommendation of a doctor. During World War II, French authorities have an abortion service for local women. When Djibouti gained its independence from France, the law was changed. The 2001 revision provided a list of 37 authorized centers that may perform abortions in the country. However, in 2014, there were no legal or regulated facilities that could provide legal abortions. Even medical facilities outside of Djibouti City, the capital, refuse to perform abortions based on religious grounds. Citizens may undergo illegal abortions at two places or have children at an early age for cultural and traditional reasons.

Abortion statistics

Government maternal mortality statistics in the decades through 2002 have been questioned as inaccurate due to its lack of breakdown, and confusion over the unit of measurement, i.e., a direct obstetrical death or an overlapping of indirect mortality.
